---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import Breadcrumbs from "../components/astro/Breadcrumbs.astro";

const crumbs = [
  { name: "Home", path: "/" },
  { name: "How We Review", path: "/how-we-review" },
];
---

<BaseLayout
  lang="en"
  title="How We Review English Learning Tools — MatchFluent"
  description="The five criteria behind every MatchFluent recommendation: speaking practice, curriculum, audio authenticity, pricing honesty, and access."
  path="/how-we-review"
>
  <main class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6 py-10">
    <Breadcrumbs {crumbs} />
    <h1 class="font-display text-4xl font-bold text-navy-700 mb-6">How We Review</h1>

    <article class="space-y-6 text-text-secondary leading-relaxed">
      <p class="text-lg text-navy-700">
        Every tool MatchFluent recommends — or recommends against — is evaluated on the same five
        criteria, weighted toward the one outcome that matters: can a learner actually speak English
        after using it?
      </p>

      <ol class="list-decimal pl-5 space-y-4">
        <li>
          <strong class="text-navy-700">Speaking practice quality (highest weight).</strong> Does the
          tool make you produce spoken English, and does it give feedback on what you said? Minutes
          of learner speech per session and the presence of pronunciation feedback separate speaking
          tools from recognition drills.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong class="text-navy-700">Curriculum structure.</strong> Is there a progressive path
          that decides what comes next and schedules review — or a loose content library that leaves
          sequencing to the learner?
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong class="text-navy-700">Audio authenticity.</strong> Real native-speaker
          conversation at natural (or deliberately staged) speed versus synthesized snippets and
          gamified sound effects.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong class="text-navy-700">Pricing honesty.</strong> Total cost over a realistic
          learning timeline (12–18 months), not the teaser price. Subscriptions are compared against
          one-time purchases at the durations learners actually need.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong class="text-navy-700">Access and portability.</strong> Offline use, device
          coverage, and whether you keep access to what you paid for if you pause.
        </li>
      </ol>

      <p>
        We test tools hands-on against these criteria and revisit reviews when products change
        materially. We do not accept payment for placement in rankings, and no vendor sees a review
        before publication. Some links on review pages are affiliate links — disclosed on every page
        where they appear and explained in full in our
        <a href="/affiliate-disclosure/" class="text-teal-700 underline">affiliate disclosure</a>.
        Commissions never change a verdict: several of our top recommendations (Duolingo, BBC
        Learning English, Anki) earn us nothing.
      </p>

      <p>
        Where we publish specific figures — prices, hours, timelines — they reflect vendor pricing
        and published research at the time of writing, hedged honestly where certainty isn't
        available. Found something outdated? We want to know.
      </p>
    </article>
  </main>
</BaseLayout>
